<br>
 Daon's father opened the door to the unholy room, hidden underneath the city of Freeport. Daon, not disturbed by the sudden appearance, slowly lifted his young, clean shaven face to look at his father. He was a Shadow Knight. As was Daon's mother. Every generation of his family was loyal to Innoruuk. His father's face never showed any emotion but anger or sick joy at others suffering. Unlike Daon, who never showed any emotion at all. He was always still as a statue. Tall and dark. Many women considered him handsome even angelic, but the dark aura about him always frightened away the women, who did not serve Innoruuk. The women who did not know of his family's true religion. At times this irked Daon. Most of the women of The Dismal Rage didn't pay attention to him. But Daon did not give it too much thought. Self pity was not in his nature.<br>
<br>
 &quot;The Knights of Marr, discovered the bodies of those you slain earlier, Daon&quot; His father said. &quot;They do not know it was you, but you will need to be careful. They send adventurers to hunt the tunnels. Be alert when you use the tunnels again to leave the city. Your mother wishes to speak to you.&quot;<br>
 As suddenly as he appeared, Daon's father left. There was little, if any, show of affection in Daon's family life. The only &quot;truly&quot; emotional one was Daon's mother. A woman as cold as she was beautiful, but she always had a smile on her full lips. The smile matched the twinkle in her eyes, but the smile wasn't for her liking someone. She smiled because she knew she could kill almost anyone. In more ways than physical, even. She was known as one of the few, if any, human women to manipulate Dark Elf men, as easily as human men.<br>
<br>
 &quot;Come in&quot; Daon's mother said when he knocked. She was dressed in a beautiful set of decorated, black leather armor. She wore it for the feel of the leather on her skin, more than for protection. The leather had once been human skin. &quot;I want you to assist some Teir'Dal &quot;friends&quot; of mine, on one of their hunts in the West Commons.&quot; She watched Daon for a reaction. He was a loner by nature. Anything that disturbed someone, no matter how minor, amused her. She fed on people's emotions like a succubus. Daon made no movement. He stood tall and straight like a statue. His face, framed by his raven, black hair, showed no emotion. Not even his blue eyes. Daon's mother scowled. She never could, in all Daon's nineteen years, get a reaction out of him. As a young child, he never flinched, even when yelled at and punished. The Teir'Dal she knew, were more jumpy than her son. She liked that, but hated it at the same time. She never liked anyone being immune to her manipulations, no matter how subtle her manipulations were.<br>
 <br>
 &quot;...Anything else?&quot; was all Daon said. Simply. With his calm, slightly deep voice. His voice wasn't the deep, gruff voice of most barbarians or bragging warriors in bars. It was a calm, precise, masculine voice that could either charm most people. Or frighten most people, if he spoke to them from the shadows of the city tunnels, before he killed them.<br>
