<br>
     &quot;....Make up your minds.&quot; Daon said. Slowly, calmly. His voice drawing out the &quot;i&quot; in &quot;minds&quot; a little. Just a little. Enough to make it sound almost like a low, subtle growl. &quot;...Either you are going to kill me...or you are the Teir'Dal, I am to accompany to the West Commonland.&quot; Daon wasn't afraid of them all attacking him at once. They were like him, he knew now. &quot;Choosen ones&quot;. There were great powers at work in the universe. Powers of Order and Discord. More and more often, people were born as &quot;Choosen Ones&quot;. <br>
<br>
     Immortal in a sense. They could die, but they were always reborn to a location their soul was familiar with. &quot;Choosen Ones&quot;, whether considered evil or good, could make an impact on events in the world. Not always. But &quot;Choosen Ones&quot; had more of a chance than most mortals. There was one special rule among them. No &quot;Choosen One&quot; could directly harm another, unless challenged and the challenge accepted. In some areas, no one was safe. But the tunnels of Freeport was a &quot;normal&quot; location, as far as the Powers of Order and Discord were concerned. The Teir'Dal could not attack him here, if Daon did not wish to fight. And not all of them at once.<br>
<br>
     The Teir'Dal woman said his name. She was a friend of his mother. She commented on his stealth, but said she could still feel his presence. She was skilled, Daon knew. Daon was no novice to moving quietly and unseen. He would have to be careful around these Teir'Dal. They knew what they were doing. The woman told Daon to pick up the body and carry it with them. Better to leave no evidence, besides the blood. Daon stood there quietly, for a moment. His eyes staring calmly into the Dark Elf woman's. Then he walked away from the group, towards the darker tunnels of the Freeport sewers, to find the hidden exit. He didn't say a word to them or acknowledge their complaints when he left them with the body. He would wait for them at the hidden exit. Daon saw no need to baby the Dark Elves. He could hear their complaints echoing down the tunnels as he waited. The Teir'Dal didn't seem to like having to do their own work, after telling someone else to do it. Daon smiled inwardly, though his face was as passive as ever. His amusement was disturbed by the sound of movement behind him. Someone found the hidden tunnel from the outside. Someone who drew their blade, a longsword. Someone who was holding that longsword to Daon's throat, challenging him to a duel. Someone who told Daon to draw his steel and die....<br>
<br>
