<br>
     Daon made his way to the main room of the Dismal Rage guildleaders and merchants. It was the first room to pass by for anyone searching the tunnels. Who better to protect the Dismal Rage than some of their most powerful teachers? The merchants themselves, were all experienced fighters in their own right. Daon fell out of the shadows of the tunnel and collapsed near the feet of a Necromancer trainer.<br>
<br>
   Daon awoke hours later, in one of his family's rooms. In a far away corner of the territory of the Dismal Rage, beneath Freeport.  His wounds healed but the pain of his right arm lingered. He felt his right hand, reattached by magic, occasionally twitching in a bowl of blood. The bowl wasn't filled with water stained with blood, the bowl was actually filled with blood. Who's, he did not know. Nor did he care. The pain was still there. The hand was restored, but the pain would last for hours until the magic process was complete. When suffering incredible pain, the mind loses some ability to think clearly. Emotions tend to be at their peak. Daon lifted his blood covered hand to look at what may have been lost forever, then placed his hand back into the bowl. Daon's eyes were always calm and looked cold when fighting and killing. With the pain infecting his mind, Daon had a feral snarl on his face. His eyes intense with violent potential. He sat in the room alone, no light but one candle in the corner, briefly illuminating his features with the unsteady flame. Daon was in pain and he wanted all of Norrath to scream because of it.<br>
<br>
     &quot;The TeirDal said Daon won the fight with the knight by using a clever tactic.&quot; Daon's father said in a low tone. He and Daon's mother were in a nearby room, surrounded by several lit candles. Daon's father paced the room while Daon's mother lounged on a pile of furs. Incense filled the air. &quot;Then he was not strong enough to win.&quot; Daon's mother mused, more to herself than to her husband. &quot; Although strategy is a good thing, he was weaker than the Paladin.&quot; She leaned back against the pile of furs and relaxed her still young body. She knew being ruthless and sexual was an attraction her husband could not ignore. &quot;Perhaps we should kill him as we did his sister. She was unable to learn any good skills and therefore was useless. Daon has been exceptional.&quot; She caressed her bottom lip with her index finger. &quot;Until now.&quot; Daon's father unbuckled his sword belt and approached his wife. &quot;No. We wait until after my group assaults the Hall of Truth in a few days. That will give me time to think of his value to the Dismal Rage. If he is of no use, I will kill him myself.&quot;<br>
<br>
     In the darkness of the room Daon was in, his mind was assaulted by the pain of his healing hand. The rage that all Shadowknights have, building up in response to that pain. His deep blue eyes, the only thing now illuminated by the candle light, staring straight ahead. His eyes intelligent and focused with an inhuman clarity, despite the condition of his mind. His every sense, sharpened to a painful, above normal accuracy.<br>
<br>
     Daon's mother and father made their plans. Their son, the killer in the dark, was listening.<br>
<br>
