<br>
      His family will kill him, he knew, if Daon did not prove his usefulness to the Dismal Rage. He could kill them. It may be easy. It may not. The image of his father's eyes opening up just in time to see Daon swinging a greatsword pleased Daon. His mother would obviously be awake after father was dead. Even unarmored and weaponless, she would be dangerous. She had always been the more powerful of Daon's parents, though Daon's father did not know this.<br>
      <br>
       &quot;Never let the enemy know your full potential&quot; she told Daon one night. While casually hacking off a young Bard's legs, as the Bard tried to crawl away. Screaming with each cut of the large greatsword Daon's mother wielded. Hands shaking, the bard looked like a turtle, slowly attempting to run from a predator. The Bard stopped screaming when Daon's mother finished chopping off both his arms. The Bard's mouth was wide open in a final, silent scream as his eyes rolled up into his head. The Bard suddenly vomited blood, after Daon thought he was already dead, shuddered, then was still. Daon slowly followed beside his mother throught out the slow murder. While looking down at the body, Daon's face was as statue-like as ever. Daon was six years old.<br>
<br>
      His mother could cast a spell on Daon, by the time he moved into position to attack his mother. Shadows to slow him down and possibly even burn the blood inside his veins. Enough time to grab a weapon of her own. If he succeeded, what then? The Dismal Rage might not look at the situation as survival of the fittest. They would &quot;forget&quot; Daon's passing though. His parents were higher in rank than him. Daon starred at the door. His right hand gripping the handle of the greatsword. He felt a sense of power holding any weapon. Then he felt like a common thug.<br>
<br>
     Any idiot can just attack. Not all Shadowknights had honor. Daon choose to. He could prove his worth, not to his family, but to the Dismal Rage. Using one of the &quot;gifts&quot; of being a &quot;Choosen One&quot;, Daon sent a psychic message to the Teir'Dal woman he meet earlier. Daon was going hunting.<br>
<br>
      In Surefall Glade, Myna was oiling her swords, when she heard a visitor approach her door. She opened the door before the man could knock. The &quot;guest&quot; from earlier had arrived. He had a empty look in his eyes. She could have stabbed him right then, and Myna doubted he would notice.<br>
<br>
     &quot;My son is dead. He is not coming back. His soul is tired from the horror he endured.&quot; The man shook his head. &quot;My son is gone.&quot; Myna was trying to come up with a proper phrase to say at moments like this. A phrase meant to comfort but usually sounded hollow to her ears. The man handed her a bag full of coins, surprising Myna. She had been glancing at the ceiling, trying to think of something to say. &quot;Kill him.&quot; The man said simply. There was nothing simple about the look on his face. Quiet, tight lipped hatred was easy to read on his features. It seemed, to Myna, that Innoruuk, deity of Hatred, won no matter what. Myna didn't need to ask whom, that was simple to guess. &quot;His name is Daon, right?&quot; Myna asked. &quot;Your son heard the priest say his name, before the Shadowknight killed him...right?&quot; The man nodded his head and walked away into the night. <br>
<br>
     Myna finished putting on her armor, placed both her long swords into her belt sheaths with a click, then walked out her house and into the night air.<br>
